1
00:00:51,000 --> 00:00:52,600
She likes you.

2
00:00:54,600 --> 00:00:55,600
You see, Melanie...

3
00:00:55,800 --> 00:00:58,200
...she's every bit as pretty.

4
00:01:08,200 --> 00:01:10,200
You've been very nice.

5
00:01:10,700 --> 00:01:12,900
Now you can have what you want.

6
00:01:26,400 --> 00:01:27,500
Hey, you!

7
00:01:28,000 --> 00:01:29,200
Birdboy!

8
00:01:42,700 --> 00:01:46,000
Mrs. Angelucci said them feathers
can give you asthma.

9
00:02:01,700 --> 00:02:03,400
I've got a great idea.

10
00:02:04,300 --> 00:02:05,600
Let's enlist.

11
00:02:15,900 --> 00:02:17,200
Kids got to play, honey.

12
00:02:17,500 --> 00:02:19,400
Go tell that to your son.

13
00:02:29,500 --> 00:02:31,200
Birdy!

14
00:02:32,100 --> 00:02:33,600
Are you all right?

15
00:02:56,000 --> 00:02:57,200
Switch shifts on Thursday?

16
00:03:00,600 --> 00:03:02,600
How come they didn't
change the bandages?

17
00:03:02,800 --> 00:03:05,100
No, ma'am.
He's unavailable right now.

18
00:03:05,400 --> 00:03:07,100
Can I have him call you?

19
00:03:15,900 --> 00:03:17,200
That's Doctor Moore.

20
00:03:54,400 --> 00:03:55,800
How long do I wear these things?

21
00:03:56,100 --> 00:03:59,200
We'll take them off when you
get back from seeing your friend.

22
00:03:59,500 --> 00:04:02,300
Then I'll see if you got
everything back in the right place.

23
00:04:02,500 --> 00:04:05,600
Should be okay,
give or take an ear or two.

24
00:04:06,300 --> 00:04:09,000
I think the graft is
going to be just fine, Al.

25
00:04:09,700 --> 00:04:13,200
After a while it'll start itching,
but you can't scratch it.

26
00:04:15,500 --> 00:04:17,000
This ought to hold you.

27
00:04:17,300 --> 00:04:18,500
How do you feel?

28
00:04:20,100 --> 00:04:21,900
Like the Invisible Man.

29
00:04:22,300 --> 00:04:24,200
Come see me when you get back, okay?

30
00:04:24,400 --> 00:04:25,600
Sure thing.

31
00:04:25,800 --> 00:04:27,100
Don't worry.

32
00:05:35,200 --> 00:05:36,600
Don't stare, honey.
It's rude.

33
00:05:44,900 --> 00:05:46,400
Shit, Birdy.

34
00:05:46,600 --> 00:05:48,400
The things you put me through.

35
00:05:49,200 --> 00:05:52,200
They always said you were weird.
Even my kid brother.

36
00:05:52,800 --> 00:05:54,800
Do you remember the time
with the knife?

37
00:06:22,600 --> 00:06:24,800
Jesus Christ!
These damn kids!

38
00:06:25,500 --> 00:06:28,800
Way to go! Now we'll never
get it back. The lady's a witch.

39
00:06:29,200 --> 00:06:30,200
Stay out of my yard!

40
00:06:30,500 --> 00:06:31,300
You hear?

41
00:06:31,500 --> 00:06:34,300
We don't have another ball.
How else we going to play?

42
00:06:34,600 --> 00:06:37,000
By not hitting it here.
Go somewhere else and play.

43
00:06:37,200 --> 00:06:40,100
This ain't no ballpark.
This is my yard.

44
00:06:41,900 --> 00:06:43,400
Why don't you do something about it?

45
00:06:44,000 --> 00:06:45,100
Kids got to play, honey.

46
00:06:45,300 --> 00:06:47,100
You tell that to your own boy.

47
00:07:04,000 --> 00:07:05,300
I don't want to.

48
00:07:05,600 --> 00:07:07,000
Come on, why not?

49
00:07:07,600 --> 00:07:08,800
I just don't feel like it.

50
00:07:09,000 --> 00:07:10,900
Sure you feel like it.

51
00:07:15,200 --> 00:07:16,500
Well, if I let you...

52
00:07:16,700 --> 00:07:18,600
...can I wear your letter jacket?

53
00:07:19,400 --> 00:07:20,200
Yes.

54
00:07:20,600 --> 00:07:21,400
Hey, Al.

55
00:07:21,700 --> 00:07:22,800
-Al!
-What?

56
00:07:23,000 --> 00:07:24,900
He's down the street.
The weird kid.

57
00:07:25,100 --> 00:07:26,400
Later, Mario. Get lost.

58
00:07:26,700 --> 00:07:28,700
Come on, you promised.

59
00:07:42,600 --> 00:07:44,100
Hey, birdboy!

60
00:07:46,700 --> 00:07:47,800
What's your name?

61
00:07:52,000 --> 00:07:54,200
This is like talking to the air.

62
00:08:09,000 --> 00:08:11,800
Got a knife I can borrow, kid?
Got a splinter.

63
00:08:19,400 --> 00:08:20,200
This it, Mario?

64
00:08:20,500 --> 00:08:21,900
Yeah, that's my knife.

65
00:08:22,100 --> 00:08:24,000
You thief!
My brother says it's his.

66
00:08:24,600 --> 00:08:26,200
Back off!
Don't mess with me!

67
00:08:26,400 --> 00:08:27,900
Don't mess with my brother!

68
00:08:28,200 --> 00:08:29,700
He's a wrestling champion!

69
00:08:43,000 --> 00:08:45,600
Now you're in trouble!
This really better be your knife.

70
00:08:46,100 --> 00:08:47,800
It is.
Ziegenfuss stole it from me.

71
00:08:48,000 --> 00:08:49,800
I thought you said he stole it!

72
00:08:50,000 --> 00:08:51,400
No! I just said he had it.

73
00:08:52,500 --> 00:08:53,400
Jesus, Mario.

74
00:08:55,000 --> 00:08:58,000
I bought it from Ziegenfuss.
But if he stole it, you can have it.

75
00:08:59,200 --> 00:09:00,000
Don't touch it.

76
00:09:00,500 --> 00:09:02,400
-It's mine.
-We'll get you another.

77
00:09:02,700 --> 00:09:03,600
Here.

78
00:09:05,300 --> 00:09:06,300
Thanks.

79
00:09:09,100 --> 00:09:12,000
Where'd you learn all that stuff?
You wrestle or something?

80
00:09:12,200 --> 00:09:13,200
No.

81
00:09:13,800 --> 00:09:15,100
You should.

82
00:09:16,600 --> 00:09:17,400
You like pigeons?

83
00:09:18,200 --> 00:09:19,400
What's to like?

84
00:09:19,600 --> 00:09:20,800
They fly.

85
00:09:21,000 --> 00:09:22,100
They fly. So what?

86
00:09:23,400 --> 00:09:24,700
That's enough.

87
00:09:26,800 --> 00:09:28,600
Come on, Al. Are we going, or what?

88
00:09:30,400 --> 00:09:32,700
I'm training these
to be carrier pigeons.

89
00:09:33,500 --> 00:09:35,400
You mean with the notes,
like in a war?

90
00:09:38,200 --> 00:09:40,400
I got a class. I've got to go.

91
00:09:40,600 --> 00:09:41,600
So go.

92
00:09:41,800 --> 00:09:43,000
Up yours!

93
00:09:47,200 --> 00:09:48,300
Pretty ugly birds.

94
00:09:48,600 --> 00:09:52,200
You know, if he really can train
them to carry notes, I'd buy one.

95
00:09:52,500 --> 00:09:55,400
-You would?
-Sure. A lot of kids would.

96
00:10:00,100 --> 00:10:01,400
Wait a minute!

97
00:10:02,500 --> 00:10:04,800
How about if I help you catch some?

98
00:10:24,600 --> 00:10:26,300
It's funny how they do that.

99
00:10:26,700 --> 00:10:29,700
If it hadn't happened every
five minutes for the last 50 years....

100
00:10:29,900 --> 00:10:30,800
Dumb.

101
00:10:31,000 --> 00:10:32,500
They always come back
to the same place.

102
00:10:34,200 --> 00:10:35,200
See?

103
00:10:35,500 --> 00:10:38,800
Same exact spot every time, and just
carry on with their business.

104
00:10:39,000 --> 00:10:40,800
-Come on.
-Where you going?

105
00:10:41,000 --> 00:10:42,000
Higher.

106
00:10:42,300 --> 00:10:44,900
-We got to get up to talk to them.
-Are you kidding?

107
00:10:46,800 --> 00:10:48,600
Are we allowed up here?

108
00:10:49,100 --> 00:10:50,400
Looks awful high to me.

109
00:11:17,400 --> 00:11:18,500
Fuck you!

110
00:11:40,900 --> 00:11:41,800
It worked!

111
00:12:24,400 --> 00:12:26,000
Birdy, where are you?

112
00:12:29,500 --> 00:12:32,000
Very funny.
Now where the fuck are you?

113
00:12:32,800 --> 00:12:35,400
Come the hell out.
I know you're in here, birdbrain.

114
00:12:40,500 --> 00:12:41,500
What's that?

115
00:12:44,000 --> 00:12:45,800
A pigeon suit I'm making for you.

116
00:12:48,600 --> 00:12:50,600
This way, they'll think
you're one of them.

117
00:12:52,500 --> 00:12:54,600
I don't want them to think
I'm one of them.

118
00:12:55,600 --> 00:12:56,900
Come on, just try it.

119
00:13:00,300 --> 00:13:02,200
No way would I be caught dead in that.

120
00:13:12,400 --> 00:13:13,600
I feel ridiculous.

121
00:13:14,000 --> 00:13:15,200
You look terrific.

122
00:13:15,500 --> 00:13:16,300
Come on.

123
00:13:16,500 --> 00:13:17,800
It's over here.

124
00:13:32,700 --> 00:13:34,400
I want to go change.
I look stupid!

125
00:13:34,700 --> 00:13:36,300
Not to a bird, Al.

126
00:14:08,700 --> 00:14:10,300
That's some view.

127
00:14:10,700 --> 00:14:12,600
Can you see the Tower Theatre?

128
00:14:13,000 --> 00:14:15,200
That must be City Hall over there.

129
00:14:17,200 --> 00:14:18,600
Stars, Al.

130
00:14:18,800 --> 00:14:20,600
Look at the stars.

131
00:14:21,200 --> 00:14:22,700
What stars?

132
00:14:24,200 --> 00:14:26,200
We should come back
to just look at them.

133
00:14:28,400 --> 00:14:31,200
What are you doing?
For chrissakes, get down!

134
00:14:37,600 --> 00:14:39,300
Hold my legs, will you, Al?

135
00:14:42,800 --> 00:14:44,400
You'll like this one, Al.

136
00:14:45,300 --> 00:14:47,000
She looks like your dad.

137
00:14:48,700 --> 00:14:50,400
I got to get a little lower.

138
00:14:50,600 --> 00:14:51,800
Let me down a bit more.

139
00:14:52,700 --> 00:14:54,200
Jesus, Birdy!

140
00:14:54,800 --> 00:14:56,000
Give me a bag.

141
00:15:01,900 --> 00:15:03,100
Fuck!

142
00:15:08,900 --> 00:15:10,600
No! Birdy!

143
00:15:13,000 --> 00:15:14,200
Hold on, I'll get help.

144
00:15:15,300 --> 00:15:16,700
I can't hold on that long.

145
00:15:17,000 --> 00:15:18,600
What's so funny?

146
00:15:19,300 --> 00:15:20,200
You.

147
00:15:20,400 --> 00:15:21,300
You look so serious.

148
00:15:21,600 --> 00:15:23,100
It is fucking serious!

149
00:15:25,100 --> 00:15:26,200
Shit!

150
00:15:27,600 --> 00:15:29,600
Look, this isn't going to work.

151
00:15:30,300 --> 00:15:32,500
I'll try to make it to the sand pile.

152
00:15:32,700 --> 00:15:34,600
-What are you talking about?
-It's easy.

153
00:15:34,900 --> 00:15:35,800
You'll jump?

154
00:15:36,300 --> 00:15:38,800
No, Al, I'm going to fly.

155
00:15:39,000 --> 00:15:39,900
Don't jump!

156
00:15:40,200 --> 00:15:41,300
Let go!

157
00:16:19,400 --> 00:16:21,100
Birdy, are you all right?

158
00:16:24,300 --> 00:16:26,500
Birdy, are you all right?

159
00:16:28,000 --> 00:16:29,000
I flew, Al.

160
00:16:29,200 --> 00:16:30,400
Sure, you flew.

161
00:16:30,600 --> 00:16:32,000
It was beautiful.

162
00:16:34,200 --> 00:16:35,800
It was like....

163
00:16:37,100 --> 00:16:38,800
You look awful pale, Birdy.

164
00:16:39,000 --> 00:16:40,400
Should I go get somebody?

165
00:16:40,800 --> 00:16:43,000
You might have busted something inside.

166
00:16:43,400 --> 00:16:46,000
You'll break your crazy neck
one of these days.

167
00:16:51,800 --> 00:16:54,600
God, Birdy!
Don't do anything like that again.

168
00:17:08,700 --> 00:17:10,300
What do you think, sergeant?

169
00:17:11,600 --> 00:17:12,600
Sir?

170
00:17:12,800 --> 00:17:14,000
Your friend.

171
00:17:14,200 --> 00:17:16,100
How does he look to you?

172
00:17:16,300 --> 00:17:19,300
It's hard to say.
I'm not sure I understand your question.

173
00:17:19,600 --> 00:17:20,900
It's a simple question.

174
00:17:21,100 --> 00:17:22,800
How does your friend look?

175
00:17:23,600 --> 00:17:25,300
Are you his doctor?

176
00:17:26,800 --> 00:17:28,500
Why are you asking me?

177
00:17:29,000 --> 00:17:32,200
Obviously, because I want to hear
what you have to say.

178
00:17:34,300 --> 00:17:37,500
He doesn't look good.
Does he just sit there like that?

179
00:17:37,700 --> 00:17:39,200
For the most part.

180
00:17:39,900 --> 00:17:40,800
Was he wounded?

181
00:17:41,100 --> 00:17:42,700
Yes, but his wounds
were relatively minor.

182
00:17:42,900 --> 00:17:45,000
This is not a physiological condition.

183
00:17:45,200 --> 00:17:46,800
Then how'd he get like this?

184
00:17:47,000 --> 00:17:50,400
All we know is that he was
missing in action for a month.

185
00:17:50,600 --> 00:17:52,800
For a while, we didn't even
know who he was.

186
00:17:53,000 --> 00:17:54,300
Does he know who he is?

187
00:17:54,500 --> 00:17:55,700
I don't know.

188
00:17:56,000 --> 00:17:58,000
He hasn't talked since he was found.

189
00:17:58,600 --> 00:18:01,000
So you really don't know anything.

190
00:18:01,200 --> 00:18:04,100
I think I know a few things, sergeant.

191
00:18:04,300 --> 00:18:06,500
It was my idea to bring you here.

192
00:18:07,400 --> 00:18:08,800
Why am I here?

193
00:18:09,100 --> 00:18:11,300
The patient's mother
thought you might be...

194
00:18:11,500 --> 00:18:13,400
...well, of some help.

195
00:18:13,700 --> 00:18:16,100
Frankly, I'm willing to try anything.

196
00:18:16,800 --> 00:18:18,900
-And I'm it?
-For now.

197
00:18:20,200 --> 00:18:22,100
When I found out about
your condition....

198
00:18:23,700 --> 00:18:26,400
It seems like it might be
an interesting therapy.

199
00:18:28,000 --> 00:18:29,200
For him or for me?

200
00:18:29,400 --> 00:18:31,100
I hope for both of you.

201
00:18:31,300 --> 00:18:34,000
Come with me.
There's something I want you to see.

202
00:18:41,400 --> 00:18:43,000
No, tuna salad, not chicken salad.

203
00:18:43,300 --> 00:18:45,800
Lots of mayonnaise and none of those
little celery chunks.

204
00:18:46,000 --> 00:18:47,000
Two of them.

205
00:18:47,200 --> 00:18:48,400
Do you want anything?

206
00:18:49,400 --> 00:18:50,300
Coffee?

207
00:18:50,900 --> 00:18:52,900
Two coffees, cream and sugar.

208
00:18:54,800 --> 00:18:56,300
Okay, yeah, that's it.

209
00:19:01,400 --> 00:19:02,600
Strange, huh?

210
00:19:03,700 --> 00:19:06,700
Jumping and twisting,
like he was trying to escape.

211
00:19:06,900 --> 00:19:08,700
You sure can't blame him for that.

212
00:19:08,900 --> 00:19:10,800
No one is, sergeant.

213
00:19:11,000 --> 00:19:13,100
He wouldn't like being cooped up here.

214
00:19:14,000 --> 00:19:18,400
What do you suppose impels him
into these strange positions?

215
00:19:18,600 --> 00:19:19,900
Like what?

216
00:19:20,200 --> 00:19:21,100
Like this...

217
00:19:21,300 --> 00:19:23,100
...cringing position.

218
00:19:24,000 --> 00:19:27,800
Was there any psychological trouble
before he was in the military?

219
00:19:28,300 --> 00:19:29,200
How close were you?

220
00:19:29,500 --> 00:19:32,100
We was real good buddies.
Pretty close.

221
00:19:32,400 --> 00:19:33,200
Very close?

222
00:19:33,600 --> 00:19:36,500
We weren't queer for one another
or anything like that.

223
00:19:36,700 --> 00:19:38,800
We were normal, crazy Philly kids.

224
00:19:39,000 --> 00:19:39,800
How crazy?

225
00:19:40,100 --> 00:19:41,600
You ever been to Philly, sir?

226
00:19:41,900 --> 00:19:44,400
You have to be pretty crazy
to live there.

227
00:19:47,400 --> 00:19:49,800
I don't understand yet
what's brought him to this.

228
00:19:51,000 --> 00:19:52,100
You got any ideas?

229
00:19:55,400 --> 00:19:56,600
He got drafted.

230
00:19:57,000 --> 00:19:59,000
All wars have
their casualties, sergeant...

231
00:19:59,200 --> 00:20:00,900
...and the Army takes care
of their own.

232
00:20:01,300 --> 00:20:03,000
Certainly took care of me, doctor.

233
00:20:03,300 --> 00:20:04,100
Major, sergeant.

234
00:20:04,700 --> 00:20:06,000
Major, sir.

235
00:20:06,600 --> 00:20:09,300
I know that this is difficult
for you at this time.

236
00:20:09,600 --> 00:20:12,700
And I know it's hard for you
to come here like this.

237
00:20:13,400 --> 00:20:14,500
How does your face feel?

238
00:20:15,600 --> 00:20:16,700
It's okay.

239
00:20:17,100 --> 00:20:18,000
No problems?

240
00:20:19,400 --> 00:20:22,000
The bandages are a little hard
to get used to, sir.

241
00:20:22,300 --> 00:20:23,600
When the doctor--
The major...

242
00:20:23,800 --> 00:20:27,600
...said one of the things they
had to do was give me a steel jaw...

243
00:20:27,800 --> 00:20:30,200
...I thought, "Great!
A steel jaw!

244
00:20:30,400 --> 00:20:32,400
Maybe I'll be the next La Motta."

245
00:20:32,600 --> 00:20:35,200
Turns out, a punch could knock
the pins into my brain...

246
00:20:35,400 --> 00:20:37,200
...so it's worse than a glass jaw.

247
00:20:37,400 --> 00:20:39,000
It's pretty funny, huh?

248
00:20:39,200 --> 00:20:42,000
A lot of people wouldn't think so.
Aren't you concerned?

249
00:20:43,400 --> 00:20:45,200
Sure, kind of.

250
00:20:46,500 --> 00:20:48,500
You know what would be
a good idea, Alfonso?

251
00:20:49,000 --> 00:20:51,300
-Al.
-It might be helpful...

252
00:20:51,600 --> 00:20:53,600
...if you visited your friend now.

253
00:20:54,300 --> 00:20:57,100
It's important that
I make some progress soon.

254
00:20:58,400 --> 00:21:01,200
Ronsky? Send Renaldi in here.

255
00:21:02,300 --> 00:21:05,600
You'll like Renaldi, Alfonso.
He's Italian too.

256
00:21:08,500 --> 00:21:10,400
What's going on here?

257
00:21:10,600 --> 00:21:13,300
Occupational therapy.
Some genius at Boeing thought it up.

258
00:21:14,200 --> 00:21:17,000
Who better to sort out
the nuts than nuts, right?

259
00:21:17,400 --> 00:21:19,600
-What do you do here?
-Pretty much everything.

260
00:21:19,900 --> 00:21:21,800
Mostly I help take care
of the patients.

261
00:21:22,100 --> 00:21:24,400
I take them for walks,
read them the funnies...

262
00:21:24,600 --> 00:21:26,700
...blow their noses,
change the bedpans...

263
00:21:27,000 --> 00:21:29,300
...wheel them into the TV room.
Stuff like that.

264
00:21:29,600 --> 00:21:32,100
How'd you get that shitty job?
They bust you?

265
00:21:32,300 --> 00:21:33,900
I'm a conscientious objector.

266
00:21:34,100 --> 00:21:35,400
You're kidding.

267
00:21:36,300 --> 00:21:38,100
An Italian conscientious objector?

