and not talk with you.

525
00:43:59,100 --> 00:44:01,900
Yeah, it's a real blast.
But, you know....

526
00:44:02,100 --> 00:44:04,100
Come on, Birdy!

527
00:44:05,100 --> 00:44:06,500
Talk to me.

528
00:44:09,000 --> 00:44:11,000
Okay, don't talk to me.

529
00:44:12,200 --> 00:44:14,100
You think I don't know
what you're doing...

530
00:44:14,300 --> 00:44:17,300
...with this squatting
and sideways staring stuff?

531
00:44:18,300 --> 00:44:21,200
So you're finally a bird.
Big deal!

532
00:44:23,000 --> 00:44:25,800
If Weiss finds out, he'll put
you in a display case...

533
00:44:26,100 --> 00:44:27,800
...and write papers on you forever.

534
00:45:11,500 --> 00:45:13,500
Damn cats are driving me crazy!

535
00:45:13,700 --> 00:45:15,800
I'll get a BB gun and pop them off.

536
00:45:16,100 --> 00:45:19,800
They'll give the birds a heart attack,
scaring them all day.

537
00:45:20,000 --> 00:45:23,000
Let's get this door closed
so they don't get out here.

538
00:45:23,400 --> 00:45:24,600
That's it.

539
00:45:25,800 --> 00:45:27,400
You know my mother.

540
00:45:27,600 --> 00:45:29,500
And that's Mr. Tate.

541
00:45:29,900 --> 00:45:31,600
He's deaf.
He doesn't hear anything.

542
00:45:31,800 --> 00:45:33,900
He loves the birds singing,
like Beethoven.

543
00:45:34,100 --> 00:45:35,300
I said you're like Beethoven.

544
00:45:43,400 --> 00:45:45,100
You like that one, huh?

545
00:45:45,400 --> 00:45:47,400
She's a good-looker, all right.

546
00:45:47,600 --> 00:45:50,700
But don't go for flyers when
you're looking for a good breeder.

547
00:45:53,900 --> 00:45:55,100
Come on, honey.

548
00:45:56,000 --> 00:45:57,000
Come here.

549
00:45:58,700 --> 00:46:00,300
Don't you want to eat?

550
00:46:00,800 --> 00:46:03,800
She's a pretty one,
but won't notice any of the daddies.

551
00:46:04,000 --> 00:46:06,200
She's a heartbreaker.
So particular!

552
00:46:06,400 --> 00:46:08,700
Rhett and Ashley can't get near her.

553
00:46:09,000 --> 00:46:11,000
It sure ain't like in the movie.

554
00:46:11,200 --> 00:46:14,100
I don't let them mate
more than one at a time.

555
00:46:14,300 --> 00:46:15,800
No brothers and sisters.

556
00:46:16,100 --> 00:46:18,400
It ain't right.
Says so in the Bible.

557
00:46:18,600 --> 00:46:19,500
Mr. Tate...

558
00:46:20,200 --> 00:46:22,900
...lets them all in together,
like a Roman orgy.

559
00:46:23,100 --> 00:46:24,600
Ain't natural.

560
00:46:27,200 --> 00:46:28,000
Here's Melanie.

561
00:46:28,200 --> 00:46:29,800
Come here, Melanie.

562
00:46:30,100 --> 00:46:31,400
The first day I saw Perta...

563
00:46:32,000 --> 00:46:34,100
...I knew she was special.

564
00:46:34,400 --> 00:46:36,300
The way she took to the air...

565
00:46:36,500 --> 00:46:38,200
...like it was hers.

566
00:46:44,400 --> 00:46:46,000
She likes you.

567
00:46:46,300 --> 00:46:48,400
Don't get taken in
'cause she's a flyer.

568
00:46:48,600 --> 00:46:52,400
Melanie here, she's a darling bird.
Every bit as pretty.

569
00:46:52,600 --> 00:46:54,500
No, I'll take this one.

570
00:46:58,700 --> 00:47:00,400
You can't do anything about it.

571
00:47:00,700 --> 00:47:02,700
He sold it before he ever
told me about it.

572
00:47:03,000 --> 00:47:05,200
At least we got
what we paid for the car.

573
00:47:05,400 --> 00:47:08,400
I'll give you my share.
We can use it for your ornithopter.

574
00:47:08,600 --> 00:47:10,000
I don't care about the money.

575
00:47:10,300 --> 00:47:11,400
It's the principle of the thing.

576
00:47:11,700 --> 00:47:14,600
The only principle is my old man
does whatever he wants.

577
00:47:14,900 --> 00:47:17,600
Do you want me to pin him?
I wish I could, but I can't!

578
00:47:17,900 --> 00:47:18,900
We're going to get it back.

579
00:47:19,200 --> 00:47:21,800
Are you crazy? Suicidal?
He doesn't even like you.

580
00:47:22,000 --> 00:47:23,200
He'll break your neck.

581
00:47:23,500 --> 00:47:24,400
I don't care.

582
00:47:24,600 --> 00:47:25,600
It's our car.

583
00:47:25,800 --> 00:47:27,800
You can't do this.
You know what he's like.

584
00:47:28,000 --> 00:47:29,200
I tell you, he'll kill you!

585
00:47:29,500 --> 00:47:31,700
Jesus, sometimes you're
so full of shit!

586
00:47:31,900 --> 00:47:33,900
All right, but you're on your own.

587
00:47:34,100 --> 00:47:35,600
I'm not going with you.

588
00:47:35,800 --> 00:47:38,400
I don't want blood
splattered all over me.

589
00:47:40,200 --> 00:47:41,000
Shit!

590
00:47:45,000 --> 00:47:47,000
-I want the car back.
-What do you mean?

591
00:47:47,200 --> 00:47:49,900
-You got your money!
-You had no right to sell it!

592
00:47:50,100 --> 00:47:51,600
It's worth more than the money!

593
00:47:51,900 --> 00:47:53,800
It belongs to us.
We didn't want to--!

594
00:47:54,000 --> 00:47:56,100
That car was in my name.
I'll sell it to whoever.

595
00:47:56,400 --> 00:47:59,300
Would you get out of here?
I'm trying to read my paper.

596
00:47:59,600 --> 00:48:02,400
Tell me the man's name
who thinks he bought it--!

597
00:48:02,700 --> 00:48:04,400
Get out of here. I'll call the cops!

598
00:48:04,600 --> 00:48:08,200
I was about to do that myself!
I'd like to report a stolen car!

599
00:48:08,400 --> 00:48:11,000
Are you calling me
a crook in my own house?!

600
00:48:11,200 --> 00:48:12,700
Are you crazy?!

601
00:48:12,900 --> 00:48:15,300
Are you trying to say
I stole that junk heap?!

602
00:48:15,500 --> 00:48:18,000
Don't embarrass me
in front of my family!

603
00:48:18,200 --> 00:48:20,200
You sold something that wasn't yours!

604
00:48:20,400 --> 00:48:22,800
Give me the man's name
who thinks he bought it!

605
00:48:23,000 --> 00:48:24,200
I'll tell him you made a mistake!

606
00:48:24,500 --> 00:48:27,200
I sold the car to a friend
of my brother-in-law!

607
00:48:27,500 --> 00:48:30,100
This guy is not
giving you the car back!

608
00:48:30,300 --> 00:48:33,800
You mess around with him and you'll
wind up in a concrete shirt...

609
00:48:34,000 --> 00:48:35,300
...at the bottom of the river!

610
00:48:35,600 --> 00:48:37,300
I don't want to go to the police...

611
00:48:37,500 --> 00:48:40,200
...but I got a receipt of purchase
from Mr. Russo...

612
00:48:40,500 --> 00:48:41,500
...at the junkyard!

613
00:48:41,700 --> 00:48:44,300
You think it's yours
because you registered it for us.

614
00:48:44,500 --> 00:48:47,800
It's legally ours because
you don't got no proof-of-purchase!

615
00:48:48,000 --> 00:48:50,000
Why do you want to be a hard-nose for?

616
00:48:50,300 --> 00:48:52,000
I can't get you the car back...

617
00:48:52,300 --> 00:48:54,800
-...even if I wanted to!
-So tell me his name!

618
00:48:55,100 --> 00:48:58,000
Shut up, you skinny bucket of piss!

619
00:48:58,200 --> 00:49:00,400
You're not worth going
to jail for, for murder.

620
00:49:00,600 --> 00:49:01,500
Here's what I'll do.

621
00:49:01,700 --> 00:49:03,400
-Here's the money.
-I don't want it.

622
00:49:03,700 --> 00:49:05,700
-That's all I got--
-It wasn't yours to sell!

623
00:49:05,900 --> 00:49:07,000
Shut the fuck up!

624
00:49:07,300 --> 00:49:09,100
He's going to take it.

625
00:49:09,700 --> 00:49:12,400
Read your paper, honey. Please.
He'll take the money.

626
00:49:12,700 --> 00:49:14,000
You'll take the money.

627
00:49:14,200 --> 00:49:16,600
I'll get you more from
my brother if you want.

628
00:49:17,600 --> 00:49:20,200
Don't make no trouble.
Please!

629
00:49:22,900 --> 00:49:24,400
Here.
I don't want it.

630
00:49:25,000 --> 00:49:26,800
Half of it's yours.
You deserve it.

631
00:49:27,000 --> 00:49:28,500
It was our car, Al.

632
00:49:30,300 --> 00:49:33,700
I could never stand up
to my old man like that.

633
00:49:33,900 --> 00:49:35,400
Maybe life is shitty.

634
00:49:36,400 --> 00:49:37,900
It is shitty.

635
00:49:41,100 --> 00:49:42,400
I'll tell you something.

636
00:49:43,800 --> 00:49:46,300
I'm not trying to pin life anymore.

637
00:49:46,800 --> 00:49:49,100
I don't even fucking understand it.

638
00:49:49,600 --> 00:49:53,400
I just want to make it through with
some dignity, like everybody else.

639
00:49:55,600 --> 00:49:59,400
Of course, if there was any real
dignity, there wouldn't be any sex.

640
00:50:02,000 --> 00:50:04,100
I'm going to go now, all right?

641
00:50:14,200 --> 00:50:15,200
All right?

642
00:50:20,000 --> 00:50:21,600
But I'll be back.

643
00:50:33,800 --> 00:50:35,000
Renaldi!

644
00:50:38,400 --> 00:50:40,800
Let me out! Let me out!
Let me out!

645
00:51:30,400 --> 00:51:31,800
You okay, Al?

646
00:51:32,000 --> 00:51:35,200
You were moaning as if in pain.
Is your face bothering you?

647
00:51:35,500 --> 00:51:38,900
-You won't tell anyone about this?
-No, of course not.

648
00:51:45,200 --> 00:51:46,600
No, sir, not yet.

649
00:51:48,000 --> 00:51:49,600
Yeah, he's here right now.

650
00:51:51,700 --> 00:51:53,500
His file came in this morning.

651
00:51:56,400 --> 00:51:58,200
Would you come over here, please?

652
00:52:15,500 --> 00:52:20,000
Is your serial number
10107003 or 10107008?

653
00:52:22,200 --> 00:52:24,100
It's 003. Why?

654
00:52:24,500 --> 00:52:26,500
I want to get it right.

655
00:52:28,400 --> 00:52:32,100
It's C-O-L-U-M-B-A-T-O,
Sergeant Alfonso?

656
00:52:35,000 --> 00:52:37,100
What is this?
Am I being taken prisoner?

657
00:52:37,500 --> 00:52:39,800
The major wants some more
information on you.

658
00:52:41,700 --> 00:52:42,800
What do you got, my file?

659
00:52:44,400 --> 00:52:46,500
Everything about you.

660
00:52:58,400 --> 00:52:59,700
There we go.

661
00:53:04,400 --> 00:53:07,300
Is there any history of insanity
in your family?

662
00:53:08,000 --> 00:53:08,800
No.

663
00:53:09,100 --> 00:53:10,100
Why are you asking me?

664
00:53:10,400 --> 00:53:11,600
Suicides?

665
00:53:11,900 --> 00:53:12,700
What?

666
00:53:12,900 --> 00:53:13,800
Any suicides?

667
00:53:14,400 --> 00:53:15,400
Not yet.

668
00:53:20,900 --> 00:53:23,100
Finish that later.
Bring me what you've got.

669
00:53:23,400 --> 00:53:24,600
Come on in.

670
00:53:36,300 --> 00:53:37,300
Excuse me, Major.

671
00:53:37,900 --> 00:53:39,500
Is something wrong
with your secretary?

672
00:53:41,300 --> 00:53:42,800
Oh, you mean the spitting.

673
00:53:43,000 --> 00:53:46,200
Ever since combat,
he's had a bad taste in his mouth.

674
00:53:46,400 --> 00:53:49,700
Don't worry. We're working on him.
Have a seat.

675
00:53:53,700 --> 00:53:56,300
Why was he asking me
all those questions?

676
00:53:56,800 --> 00:53:57,900
I'm not a patient here.

677
00:53:58,100 --> 00:54:00,300
I like to know who I'm dealing with.

678
00:54:01,500 --> 00:54:03,300
How do you think
the Army's treated you?

679
00:54:04,100 --> 00:54:06,500
Not bad. Okay, I guess.

680
00:54:07,600 --> 00:54:09,800
It says you attacked
a superior officer...

681
00:54:10,100 --> 00:54:11,800
...just after you arrived in Saigon.

682
00:54:12,400 --> 00:54:14,000
We were in a bar.

683
00:54:15,100 --> 00:54:16,100
I just hit him.

684
00:54:16,400 --> 00:54:18,400
You knocked out four teeth
and broke his nose.

685
00:54:18,600 --> 00:54:20,500
I hit him hard.
He was dogging me.

686
00:54:20,900 --> 00:54:23,400
-You think you might have overreacted?
-Maybe.

687
00:54:24,100 --> 00:54:25,700
Sir, we all make mistakes.

688
00:54:26,000 --> 00:54:29,700
But it's important to learn
from our mistakes. Don't you think?

689
00:54:30,200 --> 00:54:32,900
Shouldn't we be talking
about the patient here?

690
00:54:35,000 --> 00:54:37,800
Whose idea was it to steal that car?
Yours or his?

691
00:54:38,000 --> 00:54:39,300
Steal a car?

692
00:54:39,500 --> 00:54:41,500
I believe it was in Atlantic City.

693
00:54:41,900 --> 00:54:43,000
Oh, that!

694
00:54:43,200 --> 00:54:44,700
That was a misunderstanding.

695
00:54:45,000 --> 00:54:47,200
My father had it registered
in his name.

696
00:54:47,400 --> 00:54:49,600
We were having a good time, you know.

697
00:54:49,800 --> 00:54:51,500
Is that how your father saw it?

698
00:54:52,300 --> 00:54:53,500
No, not exactly.

699
00:54:54,000 --> 00:54:55,100
What did he do?

700
00:54:56,200 --> 00:54:57,500
He took away my allowance.

701
00:54:57,700 --> 00:54:58,800
Listen, you wise guy.

702
00:54:59,100 --> 00:55:01,800
I've got better things to do
than play games with you!

703
00:55:02,000 --> 00:55:03,600
I should probably
send you back.

704
00:55:03,900 --> 00:55:05,300
You don't have to do that, sir.

705
00:55:05,900 --> 00:55:07,400
Maybe you haven't noticed...

706
00:55:07,600 --> 00:55:11,100
...what happens to men like your friend,
without special attention.

707
00:55:12,000 --> 00:55:12,800
What do you mean?

708
00:55:13,000 --> 00:55:14,800
They stay here for
the rest of their lives.

709
00:55:15,000 --> 00:55:17,000
They rot.
Sometimes they just die.

710
00:55:17,700 --> 00:55:21,400
I'm sure I can get through to him.
I just need some more time.

711
00:55:23,800 --> 00:55:25,400
All right, sergeant.

712
00:55:26,200 --> 00:55:28,700
This is not an
indefinite stay for you.

713
00:55:29,200 --> 00:55:30,200
You can go.

714
00:55:33,600 --> 00:55:34,900
One more thing.

715
00:55:36,300 --> 00:55:39,000
Did you or your friend
resent your father...

716
00:55:39,200 --> 00:55:41,400
...for that misunderstanding
about the car?

717
00:55:42,300 --> 00:55:43,200
No, sir.

718
00:55:43,500 --> 00:55:45,700
We both really liked my father.

719
00:55:46,100 --> 00:55:47,700
He was a heck of a guy.

720
00:56:10,300 --> 00:56:12,000
Not so bad, right?

721
00:56:15,400 --> 00:56:18,500
Oh, shit! I should be done
with him by now.

722
00:56:18,900 --> 00:56:20,900
Would you feed him
while I go finish up?

723
00:56:21,100 --> 00:56:22,100
-Sure.
-Thanks.

724
00:56:22,300 --> 00:56:23,300
Take this.

725
00:56:23,500 --> 00:56:24,800
I'll be right back.

726
00:56:29,300 --> 00:56:31,900
I saw that cockeyed look of yours.

727
00:56:32,100 --> 00:56:34,100
That look always means something.

728
00:56:34,400 --> 00:56:36,600
You think I was hitting on her,
don't you?

729
00:56:36,800 --> 00:56:38,700
You think maybe she likes me?

730
00:56:40,900 --> 00:56:43,400
You really got to quit it
with this crap.

731
00:56:44,000 --> 00:56:45,800
I got to get out of here.

732
00:56:46,000 --> 00:56:48,100
That shrink gives me the eye
like I'm crazy.

733
00:56:48,400 --> 00:56:49,600
It's not a great feeling.

734
00:56:49,800 --> 00:56:52,000
Not that it ever
seemed to bother you.

735
00:56:54,000 --> 00:56:55,800
Come on, Birdy, eat it.

736
00:56:56,700 --> 00:56:59,200
If you could see yourself
squatting here...

737
00:56:59,400 --> 00:57:01,800
...and me shovelling
this crap down your throat...

738
00:57:02,100 --> 00:57:04,100
...you'd probably laugh
yourself to death.

739
00:57:06,400 --> 00:57:07,400
What?

740
00:57:10,000 --> 00:57:13,200
I won't have another
talking-to-the-wall conversation.

741
00:57:13,400 --> 00:57:15,200
Decide if you're listening or not.

742
00:57:21,000 --> 00:57:22,500
We'll do it your way.

743
00:57:23,200 --> 00:57:26,100
We'll sit here and commune
like goddamn birds.

744
00:58:41,900 --> 00:58:43,200
Hey, pretty.

745
00:58:47,600 --> 00:58:48,700
Come here.

746
00:58:53,100 --> 00:58:54,200
How do you do that?

747
00:59:00,200 --> 00:59:03,400
Your mother said enough for tonight.
It's almost 3 o'clock.

748
00:59:04,500 --> 00:59:06,200
I'm working on my ornithop--

749
00:59:06,500 --> 00:59:08,900
Come on, enough's enough!
We're supposed to be asleep!

750
00:59:09,200 --> 00:59:11,000
Tell him.
You're his father.

751
00:59:11,200 --> 00:59:12,400
Come on, son.

752
00:59:12,600 --> 00:59:14,200
Leave the bird alone.

753
00:59:18,700 --> 00:59:20,700
Then the bird's feather.

754
00:59:21,000 --> 00:59:24,600
It has a hollow shaft, with
feeders for blood circulation.

755
00:59:24,800 --> 00:59:27,400
On either side are branches, barbs...

756
00:59:27,900 --> 00:59:29,600
...which branch into barbules...

757
00:59:29,800 --> 00:59:32,700
...which have little barbicels
with hooks on the end of them.

758
00:59:32,900 --> 00:59:35,800
It can all be pulled apart,
like a zipper.

759
00:59:38,800 --> 00:59:40,000
And then re-zipped.

760
00:59:40,300 --> 00:59:42,400
A bird runs its beak
through its feather...

761
00:59:42,700 --> 00:59:45,000
...re-zipping feathers
that have come apart.

762
00:59:45,300 --> 00:59:47,500
Flying is much more than flapping wings.

763
00:59:47,700 --> 00:59:50,000
A bird can flap its wings
and not move an inch.

764
00:59:50,300 --> 00:59:51,600
When it wants to fly...

765
00:59:51,900 --> 00:59:54,900
...the slightest flicker
sends it up to the sky.

766
00:59:56,300 --> 00:59:59,300
You must feel that air has substance
and can hold you up.

767
01:00:00,400 --> 01:00:02,600
It's mostly a matter of confidence.

768
01:00:18,000 --> 01:00:19,900
Fuck them.
What do they know, anyway?

769
01:00:20,200 --> 01:00:23,100
Did you notice Doris Robinson
giving you the eye?

770
01:00:23,400 --> 01:00:25,800
She must be hot for
mad-scientist types.

771
01:00:26,100 --> 01:00:28,400
-You ought to ask her out.
-I don't think so.

772
01:00:28,600 --> 01:00:30,300
I can't afford to take her out.

773
01:00:30,600 --> 01:00:32,300
It doesn't cost anything.

774
01:00:32,600 --> 01:00:35,000
You think Cheryl's charging me for it?

775
01:00:35,200 --> 01:00:37,400
I'll go to the cafeteria.
You want to come?

776
01:00:37,600 --> 01:00:40,200
I want to go down and talk to my dad.

777
01:00:51,700 --> 01:00:52,800
Dad?

778
01:00:55,800 --> 01:00:56,800
Dad!

779
01:00:57,000 --> 01:00:58,000
I'm in here.

780
01:00:59,600 --> 01:01:00,800
Come on in.

781
01:01:05,500 --> 01:01:07,200
You had lunch yet?

782
01:01:07,500 --> 01:01:09,600
-I'm not hungry.
-You got to eat.

783
01:01:09,800 --> 01:01:11,800
Grab a sandwich and sit down.

784
01:01:12,800 --> 01:01:13,600
Dad...

785
01:01:13,800 --> 01:01:15,300
...I want to ask you a question.

786
01:01:16,000 --> 01:01:17,100
Shoot.

787
01:01:17,500 --> 01:01:19,900
I want another canary,
a male for mating.

788
01:01:20,200 --> 01:01:21,800
Maybe you can talk to Mom.

789
01:01:22,000 --> 01:01:24,400
I don't know.
We don't want to antagonize her.

790
01:01:25,100 --> 01:01:28,100
I had a heck of a time getting her
to let you build the aviary.

791
01:01:28,300 --> 01:01:29,800
She's worried...

792
01:01:30,100 --> 01:01:32,000
...about what it's costing
for the feed...

793
01:01:32,200 --> 01:01:33,600
...the lumber and whatnot.

794
01:01:33,800 --> 01:01:35,400
The birdseed's cheap.

795
01:01:35,600 --> 01:01:38,600
-AI and I swipe the lumber.
-I sure won't tell her that.

796
01:01:38,900 --> 01:01:41,000
She's convinced
your friend is AI Capone.

797
01:01:41,300 --> 01:01:42,200
I know.

798
01:01:43,200 --> 01:01:45,500
Don't think your mom
doesn't want what's best.

799
01:01:45,700 --> 01:01:48,200
She's concerned that you develop
interests and friends...

800
01:01:48,500 --> 01:01:50,400
...that'll help you fit in.

801
01:01:51,100 --> 01:01:52,100
Fit into what?

802
01:01:52,300 --> 01:01:54,200
Whatever. You know, life.

803
01:01:54,500 --> 01:01:57,000
She thinks I won't fit
in with AI and a canary?

804
01:01:58,000 --> 01:02:00,100
It's not that.
It's just, well....

805
01:02:00,400 --> 01:02:01,600
Take me.

806
01:02:01,800 --> 01:02:04,300
I've always had an interest in wicker.

807
01:02:04,600 --> 01:02:06,900
When I met your mom,
I could make a better wicker chair...

808
01:02:07,200 --> 01:02:09,200
...than any man in Philadelphia.

809
01:02:09,400 --> 01:02:11,800
I still could, if anybody wanted one.

810
01:02:12,100 --> 01:02:14,600
But nobody cares about wicker anymore.

811
01:02:14,800 --> 01:02:17,200
So I don't fit into
the scheme of things.

812
01:02:17,400 --> 01:02:18,800
You see what I'm saying?

813
01:02:19,100 --> 01:02:21,800
Your mother just wants you
to wind up better than me.

814
01:02:22,600 --> 01:02:24,300
Every parent wants that.

815
01:02:24,800 --> 01:02:29,500
I'm just saying you should be
interested in something practical too.

816
01:02:31,600 --> 01:02:34,500
It's hard to be good
at something nobody wants, huh?

817
01:02:38,000 --> 01:02:39,700
You really want this, don't you?

818
01:02:44,400 --> 01:02:45,800
I'll talk with your mom.

819
01:02:58,200 --> 01:03:01,100
Don't worry, I won't let him out
till you're sure of him.

820
01:03:06,000 --> 01:03:07,600
I think he's mostly bluff.

821
01:03:12,800 --> 01:03:14,200
How you doing?

822
01:03:14,400 --> 01:03:16,400
You got another one!

823
01:03:17,900 --> 01:03:19,800
-His name's Alfonso.
-What?

824
01:03:21,000 --> 01:03:22,600
He likes to fight and show off a lot.

825
01:03:22,800 --> 01:03:24,800
You named him after me.
Thanks a lot.

826
01:03:25,000 --> 01:03:28,100
-It's not really his real name.
-What's his real name?

827
01:03:28,900 --> 01:03:31,100
I don't know.
I don't speak canary yet.

